The paper discusses the implementation of a high-performance database for analyzing network data, which involves data structures and algorithms commonly used in computer science. The focus on hypersparse matrices suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The use of a lightweight in-memory database and streaming updates suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.DB (Databases) sub-category. The use of network data suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) sub-category. The use of mathematical guarantees suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category. Finally, the use of high-performance computing suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category.
